<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1583,2042]" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">
Palp as in 
<figureCitation box="[311,451,1583,1610]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[182,1407,209,1867]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[168,1419,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 12. Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A–D male palp, ventral, retrolateral, prolateral and dorsal; E, F male and female habitus, dorsal. Arrow points to dorsal patellar spines. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise. Abbreviations: Br—base of retrolateral tibial apophysis, Ce—cymbial extension, Co—conductor, Eb—base of embolus, Em—embolus, Pe—posterior tegular extension, Ta—tegular apophysis, Te—ventral tegular extension, Tr—terminal part of retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683505/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Figs 12A–D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[461,545,1584,1610]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1405,1429]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,181,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-30@14.[151,1435,181,1381]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. SEM images of the male palp of Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A ventral; B retrolateral. Arrow points to the dorsal patellar spines. Scale bars = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: Br—base of retrolateral tibial apophysis, Ce—cymbial extension, Co— conductor, Eb—base of embolus, Em—embolus, Pe—posterior tegular extension, Ta—tegular apophysis, Te—ventral tegular extension, Tr—terminal part of retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683509/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">13A–B</figureCitation>
; femur 3.25 times longer than wide, as long as cymbium; patella as long as wide, with 2 modified short and thick dorsal setae (
<figureCitation box="[664,771,1619,1646]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[182,1407,209,1867]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[168,1419,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 12. Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A–D male palp, ventral, retrolateral, prolateral and dorsal; E, F male and female habitus, dorsal. Arrow points to dorsal patellar spines. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise. Abbreviations: Br—base of retrolateral tibial apophysis, Ce—cymbial extension, Co—conductor, Eb—base of embolus, Em—embolus, Pe—posterior tegular extension, Ta—tegular apophysis, Te—ventral tegular extension, Tr—terminal part of retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683505/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Figs 12B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[783,832,1620,1646]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1405,1429]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,181,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-30@14.[151,1435,181,1381]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 13. SEM images of the male palp of Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A ventral; B retrolateral. Arrow points to the dorsal patellar spines. Scale bars = 0.1 mm. Abbreviations: Br—base of retrolateral tibial apophysis, Ce—cymbial extension, Co— conductor, Eb—base of embolus, Em—embolus, Pe—posterior tegular extension, Ta—tegular apophysis, Te—ventral tegular extension, Tr—terminal part of retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683509/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">13B</figureCitation>
); tibia wider than long, with large RTA about 2 times longer than tibia and with swollen basal part (
<emphasis box="[671,699,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Br</emphasis>
) and thin terminal part (
<emphasis box="[977,1002,1656,1681]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Tr</emphasis>
) twisted around its axis at about 150º, and round tip directed anterodorsally; cymbium elongate, 2 times longer than wide, with retrobasal extension (
<emphasis box="[1388,1419,1692,1718]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Ce</emphasis>
); bulb elongate, about 1.6 times longer than wide; tegulum with cylindrical extension in meso-retrolateral (
<emphasis box="[1353,1378,1728,1753]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Te</emphasis>
) and posterior (
<emphasis box="[267,297,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Pe</emphasis>
) parts; tegular apophysis (
<emphasis box="[595,622,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Ta</emphasis>
) 1.3 times longer than wide; conductor (
<emphasis box="[1078,1111,1764,1790]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Co</emphasis>
) relatively broad (Fig. 14A); embolus (
<emphasis box="[262,299,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Em</emphasis>
) originating at about 6 o’clock position and terminating at a 12 o’clock position, base (
<emphasis box="[1271,1302,1799,1825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Eb</emphasis>
) very wide, terminal half filamentous, tip slightly widened.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1583,2042]" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">
Female. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[449,546,1871,1898]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[182,1407,209,1867]" captionTargetId="figure-17@13.[168,1419,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 12. Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A–D male palp, ventral, retrolateral, prolateral and dorsal; E, F male and female habitus, dorsal. Arrow points to dorsal patellar spines. Scale bars = 0.2 mm, unless stated otherwise. Abbreviations: Br—base of retrolateral tibial apophysis, Ce—cymbial extension, Co—conductor, Eb—base of embolus, Em—embolus, Pe—posterior tegular extension, Ta—tegular apophysis, Te—ventral tegular extension, Tr—terminal part of retrolateral tibial apophysis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683505/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">
Fig. 
<specimenCount box="[501,546,1872,1898]" pageId="14" pageNumber="437" type="generic">12F</specimenCount>
</figureCitation>
. Total length 2.35. Carapace 0.90 long, 0.70 wide. Eye sizes: AME: 0.08, ALE: 0.06, PME: 0.05, PLE: 0.04. Coloration as in male. Measurements of legs: Fe I: 0.67, II: Fe 0.58, Pa 0.23, Ti 0.51, Mt 0.51, Fe III: 0.56, Fe IV: 0.78, unlisted segments missing
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1583,2042]" lastBlockId="15.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="438" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">
Epigyne as in 
<figureCitation box="[362,500,1979,2006]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,849,1815]" captionTargetId="figure-309@12.[151,1436,849,1815]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 11. Epigyne and vulva of Zodarion sharurensis sp. n. A, E macerated epigyne, ventral and lateral; B vulva, dorsal; C same, ventrolateral; D, F macerated epigyne, posterior; G intact epigyne, ventroposterior. Scale bars = 0.2 mm. Abbreviations: Ah—anterior hood, Cd—copulatory duct, Fo—fovea, Oc—copulatory opening, Re—receptacle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6683503" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6683503/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Fig. 11A–G</figureCitation>
; epigynal plate about 2.6 times wider than long, with distinct fovea (
<emphasis box="[1284,1315,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Fo</emphasis>
) 1.5 times longer than wide; anterior hood (
<emphasis box="[521,552,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Ah</emphasis>
) arched; copulatory openings (
<emphasis box="[903,936,2016,2042]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Oc</emphasis>
) located inside fovea; copulatory ducts (
<emphasis box="[1394,1427,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="437">Cd</emphasis>
) long, more than 2 times longer than fovea’s width, and about 9 times longer than wide; receptacles (
<emphasis box="[1290,1320,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="438">Re</emphasis>
) globular, their diameter as long as fovea’s width, separated by about 4 diameters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,285]" box="[199,1353,223,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,223,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="438">Note.</emphasis>
The generic placement is tentative, and this species most likely belongs to an undescribed genus.
</paragraph>
